<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_OrthogonalComplementSubSpace"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Orthogonal complement is subspace</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>The orthogonal complement of a set <math>
               <latex>S</latex>
            </math> in a subvector space <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math> is a subspace of <math>
               <latex>V</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>We need to show that <math>
                     <latex>W:=S^{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> satisfies the 
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>three defining properties</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <definition.ref definitionID="Def_SubVectorSpace"/>
                        <info>
                           <definition.ref definitionID="Def_SubVectorSpace"/>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Lookup these properties</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>
			of a subvector space.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>The <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>-vector belongs to <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> because <math>
                     <latex>\DotPr{\Vect{0}}{ \Vect{s} }=0</latex>
                  </math>, for every vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{s}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>S</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>To see that <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> is closed under vector addition let <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> be in <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math>. This means that, for every <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{s}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>S</latex>
                  </math>,</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{s} } = 0 = \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{s} }</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>But then</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\DotPr{ (\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}) }{ \Vect{s} } = \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{s} } + \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{s} } = 0+0 = 0</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>So <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} + \Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math> belongs to <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> as required.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>To see that <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> is closed under scalar multiplication, let <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math>. This means that <math>
                     <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{s} }=0</latex>
                  </math> for every <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{s}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>S</latex>
                  </math>. Now if  <math>
                     <latex>t</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math> is arbitrary, then</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\DotPr{ (t \Vect{x}) }{ \Vect{s} } = t\cdot (\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{s} }) = 0 </latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>So <math>
                     <latex>t\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> belongs to <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> as required.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>We have seen that <math>
                     <latex>S^{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> contains <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math> and is closed under addition and scalar multiplication. Therefore <math>
                     <latex>S^{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> is a subvector space of  <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
